# Pawl Verification Framework — Rule Index

> Guard rails for registry-driven, agent-executed development with Pawl.
> Copy the rules in this folder into your project's `.cursor/rules/` and
> adapt the `<PLACEHOLDERS>` (paths, harness command, primary metric).

| Rule | Topic |
|---|---|
| `verification-lifecycle.mdc` | Registry is ground truth; no green gate → not implemented |
| `metric-integrity.mdc` | Honest measurement; a benchmark a workaround can win is invalid |
| `no-shadow-systems.mdc` | One canonical implementation per concern |
| `honest-negatives.mdc` | Failed is a result; downstream sweep; terminal negatives |
| `project-startup.mdc` | Read before edit; big picture first |
| `verification-memory.mdc` | Query the claim index before searching or re-registering |

**Project skills** (copy `skills/` into `.cursor/skills/`):

| Skill | When |
|---|---|
| `project-startup` | Start of any substantive task — what to read by task type |
| `claim-lifecycle` | New claim, promote Planned → Verified/Failed |
| `verification-memory` | What was tried, exact results, front status |
| `honest-negative` | A claim fails — close it cleanly, sweep dependents |
| `plan-fact-check` | Verify plans against registry + code |
| `fast-iteration` | Cheap dev loops before the official gate run |
| `parallel-workers` | Multiple agent sessions without file races |

## The golden rules (one line each)

- Plans are proposals; the **registry is ground truth**.
- **No green verification → feature is not implemented.**
- Define measurable success criteria **before** implementation; freeze the gates.
- Honest negatives are first-class results; a Failed claim triggers a
  downstream sweep of everything that depended on it.
- A metric win that bypasses the measured system is a loss — reject it.
